Comment (src/views/admin/NotificationsView.vue:2467):
In the Deliveries panel, the jobs table renders whenever `!jobsLoading || jobs.length > 0`, even if `jobsError` is set and the latest request failed (which also clears `jobs`). This results in an error banner plus a misleading empty-state row (“No ... jobs match the current filters.”). Consider gating the table/empty-state on `!jobsError` (or show a distinct error empty-state) so failed loads don’t look like a valid empty result set.

Replies:
**lisa implementation guidance:** In src/views/admin/NotificationsView.vue, update the Deliveries panel so the jobs table and its normal empty-state are not rendered when jobsError is set. Change the PageCard guard around the jobs table from v-if="!jobsLoading || jobs.length > 0" to a condition that also requires !jobsError, for example v-if="!jobsError && (!jobsLoading || jobs.length > 0)". Keep the existing red error banner visible. Do not show the normal "No notification delivery jobs match the current filters." row for failed loads, because loadJobs clears jobs on a non-cursor failure and that row would imply a successful empty result. Add or update a test in src/views/__tests__/NotificationsView.spec.ts that makes the /api/admin/notifications/jobs request reject, switches to the Deliveries tab, waits for promises, asserts the error text is shown, and asserts the normal no-jobs empty-state text/table is not shown.
